<div class="header">Description</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Level 626.2.png|caption=An image of Level 626.2.|width=420px}}

This level is deceptive, and that realization usually comes far too late. The purple grassy plains seem perfect for healthy solitary reflection, with a set of rocky mountains on the horizon. These fields of purple clover constitute what we call '''Level 626.2'''. Wanderers who arrive here without knowing the true nature of the level often place too much trust in what they see. The apparent tranquility, lush vegetation, and constant silence create a false sense of refuge.

The discovery of this level occurred accidentally, when a research physician from the [[Republic of Aurielle]], searching for hydrangea (''Hydrangea arborescens'') for medicinal purposes in [[Level 626]], ended up entering an extensive path of purple clovers (''Oxalis triangularis''). Popular opinion agrees that following this path was an irreversible mistake.

{{Blurimage|file=Level 626.2-5.png|caption=A rustic structure at the entrance to a forest.|width=420px}}

At least, unlike '''Level 626''', whose atmosphere is highly toxic, wanderers here can walk freely without the need for [[Object 1|Almond Water]] or gas masks. The vegetation consists of low purple grass, purple clovers, magenta shrubs, various fungi, and small trees ranging between 25 and 65 feet in height. Although these trees are relatively rare (not as common as those in the [[Level 626|Forest of Psychosis]]), they exhibit the same indestructibility properties observed there. Studies confirm that these trees possess anomalous energy sources capable of sustaining accelerated and continuous growth.

Atmospheric observations record a complete absence of visible celestial bodies. According to all available records, the gray clouds never dissipate. The climate is permanently cloudy or rainy, and the level never receives direct sunlight. These conditions, combined with the relatively toxic pH of the soil, are responsible for the purplish coloration of all vegetation. Despite the apparent geological perfection of the plains, some points break the smooth undulation and form small mounds where several humans settle with rustic shacks made of wood, bricks, and cement, built atop giant shrubs capable of supporting extreme weight. There is no need for paved roads, as several dirt paths have already been formed, but the dirt left behind after heavier rains is undeniable.

Heavier rains receive a specific designation and display anomalous behavior. They are called '''Violet Storms''', climatic events resulting from an extremely abrupt intensification of precipitation that begins to carry an unusual energetic charge, perceptible as constant pressure in the air and a tingling sensation on the skin. Residents always prepare for these events, as they already know the winds reach high speeds and can easily destroy shacks and trees.

After the first '''Violet Storm''', no report ever again described the plains as “peaceful.”

<div class="header">Locations</div>

== The Purpleheart Museum ==
{{Blurimage|file=Level 626.2-6.png|caption=An image of The Purpleheart Museum.|width=420px}}'''The Purpleheart Museum''' is the most well-known museum within '''Level 626.2'''. Its structure is built primarily from '''purpleheart wood''', a material native to the level found inside forests and notable for its density and resistance, with the roof reinforced using layers of aged concrete. Despite the hostile environmental conditions present throughout the level, the museum remains structurally stable and has shown no signs of degradation since its establishment.

The museum remains open to any wanderer who reaches it. It functions both as a public archive and an educational space. Inside, the museum is organized into several thematic sections, focusing on the documentation of '''Level 626.2'''’s geology, botany, meteorological behavior, and past expeditions. All materials obtained in the documentation may be made available to the public by [[Level 626.2#A.D.F. Alpine Research Post|A.D.F Alpine Research Post]] (in the case of materials relating to geology, meteorology, and expeditions) and by [[Level 626.2#Violet Mycology Camp|Violet Mycology Camp]] (in the case of materials regarding botany).

No one knows for sure who was responsible for building the construction, but it is speculated that it was the research physician from [[Another Dimension Foundation|A.D.F.]] Some sections contain dedications to individuals who disappeared while attempting to document the level. This reinforces the perception that the building serves not only as an archive, but also as an informal memorial. Many gave their lives just for documentation, and having their effort honored is the least. Visitors frequently note that while sadness within the museum is expected, emotional calm is consistently regarded as a warning sign rather than a relief.

No armed presence has ever been recorded within the building (there is no need, as the community helps each other), and the museum follows an informal but strictly respected rule among sections: discussions inside remain factual, and emotional speculation is discouraged.

== The Cursed Mountains ==
{{Blurimage|file=Level 626.2-3.png|caption=An image taken atop a lower mountain. The purplish haze comes from unknown fungi. The photographer was not contaminated.|width=420px}}

The mountains on the horizon form a set we call '''The Cursed Mountains'''. They act as a natural barrier surrounding the entire level, and what lies beyond them remains a mystery. It is such a distant region that many wanderers have never even reached it, and they should consider this a blessing. Their altitude has never been confirmed, and the [[Another Dimension Foundation|A.D.F.]] is not fully certain of the geological structure of the mountains. This is due to the fact that the higher one climbs, the thinner the air becomes. At these altitudes, connections with electronic devices such as drones begin to fail, hindering biological and cartographic study of the upper regions. Recent theories suggest that '''The Cursed Mountains''' act less as geographic formations and more as a natural containment boundary for the level, although some [[Another Dimension Foundation|A.D.F.]] researchers have questioned whether the mountains contain the level or prevent something within it from leaving.

Analysis of public photographic records reveals no evidence of vegetation growth along the mountain slopes. The most detailed of these records indicates that the surface of the entire mountain range is irregular, shiny, and rocky, making proper plant growth impossible. Of course, there are exceptions; at the mountain bases and inside caves, it is possible to find purple hydrangeas that grow because the regions they inhabit receive direct rainfall. Some '''A.D.F.''' documents clearly show unusual reactions from undocumented fungi located in the mid and upper regions of the mountains when they come into direct contact with '''Violet Storms''', such as the release of spores capable of corroding metal.

There are several tents throughout the level, near forest entrances, that function as mineralogy museums administered by the [[Level 626.2#A.D.F. Alpine Research Post|A.D.F. Alpine Research Post]] and the [[Level 626.2#Violet Mycology Camp|Violet Mycology Camp]], and are fully open to visitors. They are very informative locations, and upon entering, it is possible to find several rocks: '''magnetite, nickel, chromium, salt, slate, tungsten, and molybdenum'''. The cracked wooden placards clearly indicate the origin of each material: “Stone found in hard-to-access regions of The Cursed Mountains.”

A piece of paper once found at the base of the mountains, apparently handwritten by a mountaineer, was displayed in the most famous museum of the level: [[Level 626.2#The Purpleheart Museum|The Purpleheart Museum]] — more specifically, in the “Military Honors” section. This mountaineer was on a mission involving cartography and mineral studies in undocumented areas of the mountains and disappeared without leaving any trace. His last proof of life is this note:

<div class="featurebox" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, #FFFFFF 24px, #266C91 1px);background-size:40px 25px;border-radius: 0px; margin: 1em">
<span style="color: black;"><span style="font-family:Protest Revolution;">Day 62: If anyone finds this, know that I already expected not to survive past today.</span></span>

<span style="color: black;"><span style="font-family:Protest Revolution;">Breathing here is almost impossible. The display on my oxygen tank reads 5% and keeps dropping. I am sheltered at the entrance of a cave — the tenth… or perhaps the hundredth I’ve crossed since this began. I entered to avoid the lightning from the Violet Storm, which is still perceptible outside. 4.9%. The silence in here is heavy. Suffocating. I look down: gray. I look up: more gray. Everything is the same. Why did I venture here when I could have remained in the “more lucid lands”? I just heard a piercing sound coming from deeper within the cave. I don’t know what it is, but I will go there to investigate.</span></span> 
</div>Some scientists claim the piercing sound was caused by an unidentified entity that devoured the mountaineer. Others, however, argue that death occurred due to lack of oxygen, a hypothesis supported by the note he left: “the display on my oxygen tank reads 5%.” Some believe the sound posed no danger at all — possibly the fall of a crystal — and that the mountaineer may have found an exit. There are even those who maintain the possibility of survival. After all, abandoning hope is also a form of surrender.

<div class="header">Oxalis Core</div>

Records obtained from the “Nature” section of '''The Purpleheart Museum''' describe the '''Oxalis Core'''. Within each forest, there exists a single crystalline sphere, designated the '''Oxalis Core''', informally referred to by researchers from the [[Level 626.2#A.D.F. Alpine Research Post|A.D.F. Alpine Research Post]] as “The Heart of a Forest.” The structure measures approximately 1.2 meters in diameter and is completely embedded in the soil.

The '''Oxalis Core''' receives this designation because the energy required to sustain forest growth and maintenance originates from electromagnetic pulses emitted by its core. These pulses propagate continuously throughout the surrounding environment. [[Level 626.2#Violet Mycology Camp|Violet Mycology Camp]] sensors indicate that the '''Oxalis Core''' maintains unpredictable electrical supply patterns, including during '''Violet Storms'''.

It is possible to observe, on the pillar dedicated to explaining the '''Oxalis Core''', that there was an empty glass cube inside. A small piece of paper beside the explanatory plaque clarified that upon detecting the approach of any organism, the core begins releasing energy in an extremely irregular manner, capable of causing fatal electric shocks. The absence of direct visual records is understood as a logical consequence of this behavior: the mere attempt to approach it is considered sufficient to result in immediate death.


