<div class="header-hostile">Porphyrophobia</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Level 626.2-4.png|caption=A wanderer's first-person view at the end of the phenomenon.|width=420px}}
<br>
Unlike most hostile environments, '''Level 626.2''' primarily endangers mental states rather than physical actions.

'''Porphyrophobia''' is an exclusive and highly dangerous phenomenon of '''Level 626.2'''. It occurs rarely during '''Violet Storms''', when energy accumulation reaches critical levels.

During the phenomenon, the vision of all wanderers acquires a purplish tint. Simultaneously, sticky purple plants begin emerging from the ground by the thousands. These growths spread rapidly and chaotically, eventually enveloping nearly all structures. In some cases, anomalous energy also manifests within raindrops, causing skin irritation and temporary vision loss after prolonged contact.

Sensations of mental confusion, loss of spatial orientation, and muffling of sounds are frequently reported during '''Porphyrophobia'''. A thick fog spreads throughout the level, and the sky darkens until it takes on an intense, nearly opaque violet hue. Researchers from the [[Level 626.2#Violet Mycology Camp|Violet Mycology Camp]] note that vegetation formations exhibit significantly faster growth in regions with greater human activity. Field analysts have noted that the phenomenon intensifies most rapidly in areas where wanderers previously reported feelings of calm or emotional relief. Researchers have proposed that perceived emotional stability acts as a catalyst, converting ''moments of calm into abrupt environmental hostility''.

During '''Porphyrophobia''', some wanderers also report the inability to consider their own shelters as safe environments, abandoning them even in safe conditions. No [[Object List|objects]] were detected to resolve the psychological effect. The primary danger of the phenomenon lies in the fact that '''Violet Storms''' may last minutes, hours, or even days without ceasing.

'''Porphyrophobia''' ends when the '''Violet Storm''' that caused it dissipates. When this occurs, the viscous plants gradually recede into the soil, the fog disperses, the sky regains its normal coloration, and the anomalous sensations cease.
